    "summary": "The Battle of Midway, fought June 4–7, 1942, was the decisive naval engagement of the Pacific War that permanently shifted the strategic balance against Japan. The battle pitted the Japanese Combined Fleet under Admiral Yamamoto Isoroku against the U.S. Pacific Fleet under Admiral Chester Nimitz. Japan sought to capture Midway Atoll as a forward base and lure the American carrier fleet into a decisive engagement. American codebreakers, having broken much of the Japanese naval code, had advance knowledge of the attack, allowing Nimitz to position his carriers in ambush.\n\nThe battle resulted in the sinking of four Japanese fleet carriers — Akagi, Kaga, Soryu, and Hiryu — along with their experienced air crews and hundreds of irreplaceable naval aircraft. The United States lost the carrier Yorktown. The Japanese carriers were sunk primarily by dive bombers in a matter of minutes during a crucial window of opportunity on the morning of June 4. The loss of the four carriers and their trained pilots inflicted damage on Japanese naval aviation from which it never fully recovered. The battle marked the permanent end of Japanese offensive capability in the Pacific.\n\nMidway is often called the turning point of the Pacific War. Before the battle, Japan held the strategic initiative; afterward, the Americans took it and never surrendered it. The subsequent American island-hopping campaign gradually closed in on the Japanese home islands, supported by an industrial capacity Japan could not match.",
